Exporting data from Excel

For practice, you can download the buckeye data from my website here: https://jofrhwld.github.io/data/buckeye.xls

What the menus look like will differ from one version of excel to another, and from one operating system to another, but what your goal will be is to save this excel file as a tab-delimited text file. Heres what that looks like on Excel 2011 for Macs.

With the file open in Excel, go to File > Save as

You can choose the file format youre saving as from a drop down menu towards the bottom:

From this drop down menu, you can choose either csv (for comma separated values), or the Tab Delimited File options. These are both plain text formats, and easily read into R using either the read.delim() function or the read.csv() function.

For more on reading data, look back at this section from week 2s practical.

Reshaping Data

Sometimes, youll want to take data from columns, and turn them into rows, or vice versa. For example, take the following data frame:

bad_td <- data.frame(speaker = c("speaker1", "speaker2"),
                      past_ret = c(50,45),
                      past_del = c(10, 30),
                      mono_ret = c(100, 75),
                      mono_del = c(200, 90))
print(bad_td)
##    speaker past_ret past_del mono_ret mono_del
## 1 speaker1       50       10      100      200
## 2 speaker2       45       30       75       90

Here, there is one row for each speaker,

  • past_ret = the number of past tense words each speaker produced with /t/
  • past_del = the number of past tense words each speaker produced with \(\emptyset\)
  • mono_ret = the number of monomorphemic words each speaker produced with /t/
  • mono_del = the number of monomorphemic words each speaker produced with \(\emptyset\)

This isnt a very useful data format. Think about how you might ggplot with it. Heres my best attempt at an informative plot showing the rate at which each speaker pronounce their /t,d/ in past tense forms:

  library(ggplot2)

  ggplot(bad_td, aes(speaker, past_ret/(past_del+past_ret)))+
    geom_bar(stat = "identity")

But in a lot of ways, were limited by the data format. Were not, for example, able to easily generate a plot that shows both the past tense and monomorphemic data at the same time.

This isnt just an issue about the kind of data format ggplot expects. The structure of the data in bad_td is violating principles of tidy data.

  1. Some principles of tidy data, from Wickham (2014):
  1. Each variable forms a column.
  2. Each observation forms a row.

The problem with bad_td is that the morphological class, and the kind of TD variant are both variables, but theyre being used as part of the column name.

melt()

We can easily fix the bad_td data frame by using the melt() function from the reshape2 package.

  install.packages("reshape2")

The melt() function takes three crucial arguments:

  1. a data frame to be melted
  2. a vector of id variables, that is, columns that should stay just as they are, and
  3. a vector of measure variables, that is, columns that should be turned into rows.

It makes sense when you see it in action.

  library(reshape2)

  # before
  print(bad_td)
##    speaker past_ret past_del mono_ret mono_del
## 1 speaker1       50       10      100      200
## 2 speaker2       45       30       75       90
  # you can choose columns either by their name, or numerical index
  better_td <- melt(bad_td, id = "speaker", measure = 2:5)
  print(better_td)
##    speaker variable value
## 1 speaker1 past_ret    50
## 2 speaker2 past_ret    45
## 3 speaker1 past_del    10
## 4 speaker2 past_del    30
## 5 speaker1 mono_ret   100
## 6 speaker2 mono_ret    75
## 7 speaker1 mono_del   200
## 8 speaker2 mono_del    90

By telling melt() that the measure variables were past_ret, past_del, mono_ret and mono_del, it took the names of those columns and turned it into a variable, and took the values from those columns, and collapsed them into one value column.

colsplit()

This particular example isnt quite perfect yet. The morphological class and the /t,d/ variant are two different variables, but in better_td theyre smashed together into just one column. We can split these this one column into two with the colsplit() function, also from reshape2.

colsplit() takes three arguments:

  1. The column that you want to split up.
  2. Pattern you want to use to split the column.
  3. The names of the new columns that will be created.
  print(better_td)
##    speaker variable value
## 1 speaker1 past_ret    50
## 2 speaker2 past_ret    45
## 3 speaker1 past_del    10
## 4 speaker2 past_del    30
## 5 speaker1 mono_ret   100
## 6 speaker2 mono_ret    75
## 7 speaker1 mono_del   200
## 8 speaker2 mono_del    90
  # split variable based on the underscore, "_", symbol
  new_columns <- colsplit(better_td$variable, 
                          pattern = "_", 
                          names = c("Gram", "Variant"))
  
  print(new_columns)
##   Gram Variant
## 1 past     ret
## 2 past     ret
## 3 past     del
## 4 past     del
## 5 mono     ret
## 6 mono     ret
## 7 mono     del
## 8 mono     del
  # stick these new columns onto `better_td` using `cbind()
  best_td <- cbind(better_td, new_columns)
  print(best_td)
##    speaker variable value Gram Variant
## 1 speaker1 past_ret    50 past     ret
## 2 speaker2 past_ret    45 past     ret
## 3 speaker1 past_del    10 past     del
## 4 speaker2 past_del    30 past     del
## 5 speaker1 mono_ret   100 mono     ret
## 6 speaker2 mono_ret    75 mono     ret
## 7 speaker1 mono_del   200 mono     del
## 8 speaker2 mono_del    90 mono     del

Now, we can do some useful ggploting, or statistical analysis.

  ggplot(best_td, aes(Gram, value, fill = Variant))+
      geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "fill")+
      facet_wrap(~speaker)

dcast()

Sometimes, though, you might want to go the other way, and turn some row data into column data. You can do this using dcast() from the reshape2 package.

The dcast() function takes three arguments:

  1. A data frame.
  2. A casting formula
  3. A value to fill into new cells.

The casting formula looks like this:

var1 + var2 ~ var3

The important part is what comes before the tilde, and what comes after the tilde.

var1 + var2 ~ var3

The columns that come before the tilde are going to remain just like they are in the original dataframe.

var1 + var2 ~ var3

The column that comes after the tilde is going to have its values spread out as new columns. So, lets take our current best_td dataframe:

speaker variable value Gram Variant
speaker1 past_ret 50 past ret
speaker2 past_ret 45 past ret
speaker1 past_del 10 past del
speaker2 past_del 30 past del
speaker1 mono_ret 100 mono ret
speaker2 mono_ret 75 mono ret
speaker1 mono_del 200 mono del
speaker2 mono_del 90 mono del

And apply this casting formula to it:

speaker + Gram ~ Variant

This is the basic table were going to get out:

speaker Gram del ret
speaker1 mono
speaker1 past
speaker2 mono
speaker2 past

Heres a few more examples of the table templates youd get from different casting formulas:

speaker variable value Gram Variant
speaker1 past_ret 50 past ret
speaker2 past_ret 45 past ret
speaker1 past_del 10 past del
speaker2 past_del 30 past del
speaker1 mono_ret 100 mono ret
speaker2 mono_ret 75 mono ret
speaker1 mono_del 200 mono del
speaker2 mono_del 90 mono del

+

speaker ~ Gram

=

speaker mono past
speaker1
speaker2
speaker variable value Gram Variant
speaker1 past_ret 50 past ret
speaker2 past_ret 45 past ret
speaker1 past_del 10 past del
speaker2 past_del 30 past del
speaker1 mono_ret 100 mono ret
speaker2 mono_ret 75 mono ret
speaker1 mono_del 200 mono del
speaker2 mono_del 90 mono del

+

Gram + Variant ~ speaker

=

Gram Variant speaker1 speaker2
mono del
mono ret
past del
past ret

The cells in the output of these casting formulas are blank, because you could tell dcast() to fill them with any given variable. We probably want to fill them with the data from the value column, which would look like this:

  print(best_td)
##    speaker variable value Gram Variant
## 1 speaker1 past_ret    50 past     ret
## 2 speaker2 past_ret    45 past     ret
## 3 speaker1 past_del    10 past     del
## 4 speaker2 past_del    30 past     del
## 5 speaker1 mono_ret   100 mono     ret
## 6 speaker2 mono_ret    75 mono     ret
## 7 speaker1 mono_del   200 mono     del
## 8 speaker2 mono_del    90 mono     del
  dcast(best_td, speaker + Gram ~ Variant, value.var = "value")
##    speaker Gram del ret
## 1 speaker1 mono 200 100
## 2 speaker1 past  10  50
## 3 speaker2 mono  90  75
## 4 speaker2 past  30  45

But we could also do something meaningless like this:

  dcast(best_td, speaker + Gram ~ Variant, value.var = "variable")
##    speaker Gram      del      ret
## 1 speaker1 mono mono_del mono_ret
## 2 speaker1 past past_del past_ret
## 3 speaker2 mono mono_del mono_ret
## 4 speaker2 past past_del past_ret

One reason you might want to to this dcasting is to calculate the proportion ot TD Retention in a slightly weird way.

    wide_td <- dcast(best_td, speaker + Gram ~ Variant, value.var = "value")
    wide_td$prop_ret <- wide_td$ret/(wide_td$ret + wide_td$del)
    print(wide_td)
##    speaker Gram del ret prop_ret
## 1 speaker1 mono 200 100   0.3333
## 2 speaker1 past  10  50   0.8333
## 3 speaker2 mono  90  75   0.4545
## 4 speaker2 past  30  45   0.6000

Stringing it all together with dplyr

Of course, all of these separate steps weve done can be strung together with one dplyr chain.

  library(dplyr)  
  
  bad_td %>%
    melt(id = "speaker", measure = 2:5)%>%
    cbind(., colsplit(.$variable, "_", names = c("Gram", "Variant")))%>%
    dcast(speaker + Gram ~ Variant)%>%
    mutate(prob_ret = ret/(del+ret))
##    speaker Gram del ret prob_ret
## 1 speaker1 mono 200 100   0.3333
## 2 speaker1 past  10  50   0.8333
## 3 speaker2 mono  90  75   0.4545
## 4 speaker2 past  30  45   0.6000

A Practical Example

The exercises from this week asked you to:

    1. Estimate the rate of Phrase Level Retention and Word Level Retention for each individual speaker in the Buckeye data.
    2. Evaluate how well those estimates compare to the prediction that phrase leve > word level.

Step 1: Estimate retention for each speaker for each grammatical class

  library(grammarOfVariationData)
  library(dplyr)
      
  buck_to_use <- buckeye %>% 
                  filter(Gram2 %in% c("mono","past")) %>% 
                  select(Speaker, Gram2, td)
  
  
  retention_rates <- buck_to_use %>%
                        group_by(Speaker, Gram2) %>%
                        summarise(retention = mean(td))

  retention_rates %>% head() %>% print()
## Source: local data frame [6 x 3]
## Groups: Speaker
## 
##   Speaker Gram2 retention
## 1     s01  mono    0.5806
## 2     s01  past    0.7966
## 3     s02  mono    0.5310
## 4     s02  past    0.6042
## 5     s03  mono    0.5149
## 6     s03  past    0.6000

Step 2: Divide mono/past for every speaker.

If were assuming the following:

Word Level Phrase Level
mono x x
past - x

Then in order to estimate the word level rate of TD Retention, we need to divide the monomorphemic retention rate by the past tense word rate

  1. \(\text{word} = \frac{word\times phrase}{phrase} = \frac{mono}{past}\)

One easy way to do this with the retention rates weve just calculated is to apply this casting formula to it

Speaker Gram2 retention
s01 mono 0.581
s01 past 0.797
s02 mono 0.531
s02 past 0.604
s03 mono 0.515
s03 past 0.6

+

Speaker ~ Gram2

, value.var = retention

=

Speaker mono past
s01 0.581 0.797
s02 0.531 0.604
s03 0.515 0.6 
  retention_wide <- dcast(retention_rates, Speaker ~ Gram2, value.var = "retention")

Now, its easy to divide mono by past for every speaker.

level_estimates <- retention_wide %>%
                      mutate(phrase = past,
                             word = mono/past)

level_estimates %>%
  ggplot(aes(phrase, word))+
    geom_point()+
    geom_abline()+
    ylim(0,1)+
    xlim(0,1)+
    coord_fixed()
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

level_estimates %>%
  ggplot(aes(past, mono))+
    geom_point()+
    geom_abline()+
    ylim(0,1)+
    xlim(0,1)+
    coord_fixed()
